description:
Two types represent per-epoch training results:
- neural-net.ts:19 — `TrainingState` with epoch, loss, accuracy, activations[][]
- neural-network.ts:43 — `EpochMetrics` with epoch, loss, accuracy (no activations)

Same concept, different names and shapes. Merge into one type with optional activations:
```typescript
export interface TrainingEpochResult {
  epoch: number;
  loss: number;
  accuracy: number;
  activations?: number[][];  // optional — only populated by simple NN
}
```

multi-armed-bandit.ts:26 defines `strategy: string` which accepts any string. Should be a literal union:
```typescript
type BanditStrategyName = 'epsilon-greedy' | 'ucb1' | 'thompson-sampling';

interface BanditStep {
  strategy: BanditStrategyName;  // was: string
  // ...
}
```
This enables exhaustive switch checking in consumers and prevents typos.

feature-store.ts FeatureStoreStep.action is `string`. MLDesignModule.tsx:2955 TICK_HIGHLIGHTS is `Record<string, ...>`. A typo in action creates a key TICK_HIGHLIGHTS doesn't know about — silent failure, no highlight.

Fix:
```typescript
type FeatureStoreAction = 
  | 'data-ingestion' | 'stream-computation' | 'batch-computation'
  | 'online-store-write' | 'offline-store-write' | 'training-read'
  | 'serving-read' | 'incremental-update';

interface FeatureStoreStep {
  action: FeatureStoreAction;  // narrow from string
}

const TICK_HIGHLIGHTS: Record<FeatureStoreAction, ...> = { ... };
```
Now TypeScript catches missing/mismatched actions.

MLDesignModule.tsx mode rendering at lines 983-988, 3657-3686, 3688-3715, 3717-3730 uses ternary/if-else chains that don't exhaustively check ModuleMode. Adding a new mode silently falls through to the last else (model-serving as default).

Fix: Replace with exhaustive switch statements:
```typescript
function getCanvas(mode: ModuleMode): ReactNode {
  switch (mode) {
    case 'neural-network': return <NNCanvas ... />;
    case 'pipeline-builder': return <PipelineCanvas ... />;
    // ...all cases...
    default: {
      const _exhaustive: never = mode;
      return null;
    }
  }
}
```
The `never` assignment causes a compile error if a new ModuleMode value is added but not handled.

Three step types share common fields but have no shared base:
- ServingStep: { tick, description, metrics? }
- BanditStep: { tick, selectedArm, reward, arms[], strategy }
- FeatureStoreStep: { tick, action, description, state }

All have `tick: number`. Most have `description: string`. Extract a shared base:
```typescript
interface BaseSimulationStep {
  tick: number;
  description: string;
}

interface ServingStep extends BaseSimulationStep {
  metrics?: Record<string, number>;
}

interface BanditStep extends BaseSimulationStep {
  selectedArm: string;
  reward: number;
  arms: BanditArm[];
  strategy: BanditStrategyName;
}
```
Note: BanditStep currently lacks `description` — it should be added (e.g., 'Round 5: Explored randomly, pulled Arm 3').

pipeline-templates.ts:24 uses `config: Record<string, string | number>` which accepts any key-value pair. Config keys are hand-typed strings in each template with zero type checking.

Fix: Create per-stage-type config interfaces:
```typescript
interface IngestionConfig {
  source: string;
  format: string;
  partitions: number;
  retention_hours: number;
}
interface TrainingConfig {
  model: string;
  batch_size: number;
  epochs: number;
  learning_rate: number;
  optimizer: string;
}
// ... per stage type

type PipelineStageConfig = IngestionConfig | TrainingConfig | ...;
```
This ensures config keys are correct for each stage type.

ML Design module uses ~30 useState calls in a single hook with zero persistence. All state is lost on module switch or page refresh. Create a dedicated Zustand store:
```typescript
interface MLDesignState {
  // Persisted
  lastMode: ModuleMode;
  nnConfig: { datasetType, layerCount, neuronsPerLayer, activation, learningRate, epochs };

  // Non-persisted (runtime only)
  isTraining: boolean;
  trainingLog: TrainingEpochResult[];
  trainedNetwork: NeuralNetwork | null;
  // ... other runtime state
}
```
Persist `lastMode` and `nnConfig` via Zustand persist. Keep runtime state (training results) non-persisted.
